            . I have one partner - we <rs id="t18290115-247-viclabel1328" type="occupation">keep a carpet warehouse</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290115-247-victim1885 t18290115-247-viclabel1328"></join> in <placeName id="t18290115-247-crimeloc1329">Bishopsgate-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290115-247-crimeloc1329" type="placeName" value="Bishopsgate-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290115-247-crimeloc1329" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290115-247-off1326 t18290115-247-crimeloc1329"></join>. On the 1st of January I was absent, when the carpet was taken; I saw it at the Mansion-house next day-there were thirty-six yards, which are worth 25s.</p>
               <p>JOSEPH FRVER. I am a Bow-street patrol. On the 1st of January I saw all the three prisoners together, and watched them; I first saw half an hour- I saw them standing against Mr. Fawcett's window for about twenty minutes; Briggs got on Cooper's shoulder. and they all three came together from the end of the window to the door - Briggs then pulled this carpet down off a high shelf in the shop; he could not have reached it unless he had been on the other's shoulder - Billett stood against the door at the time, and had been in their company all the time; Priggs pulled the carpet down - Billett caught it in his arms, and ran across the road with it; I secured him with it in his possession: he threw it down, and tried to get away; the other two ran up Bishopsgate-street, in different direction - I knew them before: I saw them in Shoreditch about half an hour after; they had then changed their coats; it happened at half-past four o'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290115-247-person1887">
                  JOHN 
                  ROBERTSON
               <interp inst="t18290115-247-person1887" type="surname" value="ROBERTSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290115-247-person1887" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290115-247-person1887" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable of Shoreditch. I saw the three prisoners in company, about four o'clock, within two hundred yards of the prosecutor's shop; in about half an hour I received information from Fryer, that he wanted Cooper and Briggs, and we apprehended them - I said, "Why, Cooper, you have got Briggs' coat on, and Briggs has got your jacket on;" he denied it at first, but at the watch-house they again shifted their clothes.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>BILLETT'S Defence. I had been over the water, and as I returned I saw two lads at this door knock the carpet down - I took it up, and walked over the road.</p>
               <p>BRIGGS' Defence. I was not with these lads; I had not seen them for an hour and a half before.</p>
               <p>BILLETT-<rs id="t18290115-247-verdict1330" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290115-247-verdict1330" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 21.</p>
